Date: 20 July 2026

Context: ModelHub, scrum meeting and follow-up conversation with Pavan (Tech Lead).

What happened:

1. In scrum, I and the scrum master Kamlesh questioned why a defect that had its description substantially changed by the product team (essentially becoming a different defect) before it was closed, was not raised as a new defect instead. Pavan explained a defect was raised, changes were made accordingly, and before it could be closed, the product team changed the entire description. I and Kamlesh decided to close the existing one as done and ask product to raise a new one going forward, so proper history of work is maintained and effort is counted correctly. Pavan did not agree, and raised that this particular case was from two months back. Kamlesh clarified we could apply this going forward even if it wasn't done that way so far.

2. Later, while I was discussing something with two freshers (Shruti and Apurva), Pavan interrupted in a raised voice, saying "can we please do this first, you can do that later." I responded that I understood but was working on the other item.

3. Pavan then asked to speak privately. We had an approximately hour-long conversation. Summary of his position:
   - He felt I was excluding him by asking the freshers to come directly to me for any documentation changes from product.
   - He wants to be part of every technical discussion, including defect classification changes.
   - He said he felt "attacked" by me and Kamlesh over a Jira specification question.
   - He said his interruption of my conversation with the freshers was a "repercussion" of me telling them to reach out to me.
   - He stated I am not his manager, that Shrikant is, and that we are at the same level.

4. My response: as manager I am responsible for both technical delivery and team management, not just administrative approvals. I told him he would not be excluded, but that it is neither practical nor required for me to run every conversation by him or seek permission before telling the team to reach out to me directly.

5. Pavan raised multiple hypothetical scenarios where lack of involvement could go badly. I asked whether any of these had actually happened. He could not cite one. I noted that despite this, we were having the discussion anyway.

6. I told him my role is wider and my responsibilities are different from his. I am not interested in being his manager, I know he reports to Shrikant, and for that reason I have not asked him any managerial questions (timing, attendance, etc.). I stated clearly that as delivery manager for ModelHub, I will lead it and make decisions within my role, unapologetically.

7. I asked him directly whether he would raise these same questions with Shrikant. He said "of course not."

8. Pavan was not convinced by the end of the conversation.

9. I informed Shrikant (manager to both of us) the same day. Shrikant agreed this was wrong and said he would speak to Pavan to clarify roles and responsibilities.

10. I told Shrikant I am not holding this against Pavan, but if this pattern repeats, I will raise it formally.

Kept for record in case of recurrence.
